name: Cabbage Town
queryname: Cabbagetown, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Cabbagetown largely features semi-detached Victorian houses and is recognized as "the largest continuous area of preserved Victorian housing in all of North America".

name: Casa Loma
queryname: Casa Loma, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Casa Loma is a neighborhood named after its famous castle. Casa Loma was constructed in the early 1900s for over three million dollars and was given to the city by its heavily debt-laden owner only a decade after it was put up.

name: Danforth
queryname: The Danforth, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Crowds come for to its international mix of restaurants, cafes and bars, especially the Greek tavernas and pastry shops, as well as a vibrant mix of specialty boutiques.

name: Dufferin Grove
queryname: Dufferin Grove, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: The neighbourhood is predominantly two or three-storey detached or semi-detached homes at a medium density. The majority of Dufferin Grove houses were built between 1890 and 1930.

name: High Park
queryname: High Park North, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: The oldest residential houses in High Park North were built in the late 1800s and early 1900s and are mostly Victorian, Edwardian and Tudor-style

name: Forest Hill
queryname: Forest Hill, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Forest Hill is one of Toronto's wealthiest and most affluent neighbourhoods. It is home to many prominent entrepreneurs, celebrities, engineers, doctors, and lawyers

name: Kensington
queryname: Kensington Market, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Kensington Market is a walkable bohemian neighbourhood that draws artists and tourists to its indie shops, vintage boutiques and arts spaces.

name: Lawrence Park
queryname: Lawrence Park, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Lawrence Park was one of Toronto's first planned garden suburbs.

name: Leslieville
queryname: Leslieville, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Leslieville began as a small village in the 1850s, which grew up around the Toronto Nurseries owned by George Leslie (1804-1893) and sons, after whom the community is named.

name: Little Portugal
queryname: Little Portugal, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: The area is mainly residential, with Portuguese businesses along Dundas Street West and College Street. There is a fine stock of mid-century homes.

name: Parkdale
queryname: Parkdale, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Parkdale is a multicultural residential neighbourhood with wide, pedestrian friendly sidewalks, colourful street art and a mix of Victorian mansions and apartment buildings.

name: Regent Park
queryname: Regent Park, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Regent Park's residential dwellings, prior to the ongoing redevelopment, were entirely social housing and covered all of the 69 acres which comprise the community.

name: Riverdale
queryname: Riverdale, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Riverdale is located just east of Toronto's downtown core. Since its amendment to the City of Toronto in 1884, it has developed a stature as a neighbourhood of independent arts, with several independent galleries located along Queen Street East.

name: Roncesvalles
queryname: Roncesvalles, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Culturally, the area is known as the centre of the Polish community in Toronto with prominent Polish institutions, businesses and St Casimir's Catholic Church located on Roncesvalles Avenue.

name: Rosedale
queryname: Rosedale, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Rosedale is an affluent neighbourhood in central Toronto, Ontario, Canada. It was formerly the estate of William Botsford Jarvis, and so named by his wife, granddaughter of William Dummer Powell, for the wild roses that grew there in abundance.

name: Runnymede
queryname: Runnymede, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: The neighbourhood has two Toronto Public Library locations, Runnymede and Annette, and there is a nearby location in Swansea.

name: Swansea
queryname: Swansea, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Swansea's high-end homes are located either at the western edge of High Park overlooking Grenadier Pond, or on Riverside Drive and the Brule Gardens enclave bordering the Humber River.

name: The Annex
queryname: The Annex, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Next to University of Toronto's St. George Campus, The Annex is a lively area that draws students to its casual eateries, indie bookshops, bars and cafes on Bloor Street West.

name: The Beaches
queryname: The Beaches, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: This relaxed neighbourhood with a small-town vibe is a top summer destination, drawing families and tourists to its sandy beaches and quaint boardwalk.

name: Trinity-Bellwoods
queryname: Trinity-Bellwoods, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: The neighbourhood takes its name from Trinity Bellwoods Park, built around the former Garrison Creek ravine.

name: University
queryname: University, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: The downtown University district contains the historic main University of Toronto campus, where Gothic Revival and Romanesque buildings frame large lawns.

name: Willowdale
queryname: Willowdale, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Affluent Willowdale has cafes, eclectic restaurants, and shopping centres clustered along central Yonge Street.

name: Wychwood
queryname: Wychwood, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: Wychwood Park was founded as an artists' colony in the late nineteenth century, as a private project by painter Marmaduke Matthews and businessman Alexander Jardine.

name: York University Heights
queryname: York University Height, Old Toronto, Toronto, ON, Canada
description: York University Heights, also known as Northwood Park, is a large, multicultural area home to the main York University campus.
